a.xlink:title:
We don't have any tests for Rust features like 

fn foo<T>()
where
    for<'a> T: Trait<'a>
{}

we should fix that (and fix the borrow checker to support it!)

per the comment

    // Require only universal variables, so e.g. `forall<T> not (T: Foo)`.
    // For those, we can convert universal and existential and try to prove
    // the inverse (so try to prove `exists<T> (T: Foo)`, with a bias towards
    // completeness. If that fails, then we know that for all `T`, `T: Foo` is false.
    //
    // But with existential we can do no such trick.…

In reviewing the FIXMEs in the code, we encountered a case related to when to check that 'ensures' bounds are WF. Consider this:

trait Foo {
    type Bar: Baz<String>;
}

trait Baz<T: Copy> { }

Should it be an error? Os is the trait ok, it can just never be implemented? (perhaps a warning, which mir-formality doesn't model)

Seems related to so-called "trivial bounds"...…

From the rust

// Cycle detection: if we've already visited this block with the same live loans,
// we've reached a fixpoint and can stop recursing.…

Follow-up cleanup from PR #246:
`CoreFold` currently requires the output type to be `Self`, which prevents `apply(&(&Wcs, &Wcs))` from producing `(Wcs, Wcs)`. Changing this would let `prove_after.rs` collapse two separate `apply` calls into a single tuple destructure:
// current (two calls) (let assumptions = c1.substitution().apply(assumptions)) (let goal = c1.substitution().apply(goal))…

Follow-up cleanup from PR #246:

Pattern-matching `#[term]` enum variants with `Arc`-wrapped fields binds as `&Arc<T>`, requiring `&**var` to dereference through the Arc before Upcast can work. For example:

// current: need double-deref to get &Ty from &Arc<Ty>
Ty::My(a) => sub(&a, &b)

// desired: just use the variable directly
Ty::My(a) => sub(a, b)…

In today's formality, we never check if a variable is initialized before use, so the test below passed although it shouldn't.

crate Foo {
    fn foo () -> u32 = minirust() -> x {
        let x: u32;
        exists {
            bb0: {
                statements {
                }
                return;
            }
        }
    };
}

The test above is equivalent to…

The following code passes at the moment:

[test]
fn bad() {
    test_program_ok(
        "[crate core {
            trait Trait {}
            struct A<X> where X: Trait {}
            fn invalid<'a, X>(x: &'a A<X>) -> ()
            where
                X: 'a,
            {}
        }]",
    )
    .assert_ok();
}…

`check_trait_impl` does not verify that all required trait items are provided by the impl. This means formality silently accepts programs that rustc rejects with E0046 ("not all trait items implemented").

Reproduction

The following program passes formality but is rejected by rustc:

trait Foo {
    fn bar(self_: u32) -> u32;
}
struct MyStruct {}
impl Foo for MyStruct {}…
